    "costs": "168150",
    "actions_taken": [
      "Load test stopped immediately",
      "OIM, DSL, and STS notified",
      "Announcement made warning of slick decks from hydraulic fluid",
      "Pipe rack barriered off to prevent slip hazards",
      "Scupper plugs installed in drains to isolate LOPC",
      "Water bag recovery attempted",
      "Crane placed in cradle",
      "Inspection of brakes, motor, and crane cable by contractor and two third party crane companies",
      "BSEE Houma District office notified orally and written report submitted within 15 days"
    ],
    "summary": "On May 2, 2024, during 5-year recertification load testing of forward starboard knuckle boom crane (KBC #1) on the drillship Noble Stanley Lafosse at GC 478, a winch brake assembly failure occurred at approximately 70 MT while attempting to reach 93.5 MT test load. The crane's Automatic Overload Protection System (AOPS) activated, but brake assembly #4 failed to release simultaneously with the other three brakes. This caused excessive load on the sprag clutches which sheared, resulting in uncontrolled descent of the water bag. The descent caused a hydraulic test port failure, spraying hydraulic fluid on deck (LOPC). The water bag contacted the take-on station, ripped open, and descended to the Gulf of Mexico. Two hydraulic motors and four brake assemblies were damaged. Total property damage was $168,150. No injuries occurred.",
    "recommendations": [
      "BSEE Houma District has no recommendations at this time"
    ],
